# t/probe/memory-remember.test — ring 3 (docs/13): does a REAL agent, told to
# remember a fact, actually record one? This is the reality-dependent half that no
# offline test can cover — the worker prompt is the one surface the sim harness
# never reads, so a prompt that fails to teach the ./out/memory/ gesture passes the
# whole gate green while recording NOTHING live (the bug fixed in the commit that
# added this probe). The plumbing (harvest → remember → /memory) is proven offline
# by t/research/memory-*.test; this probe validates ONLY that a real Claude agent,
# handed "remember this", writes ./out/memory/<name>.md so the harvest has something
# to pick up.
#
# Run it live (real Claude + Fastmail), one agent turn — cheap:
#     ./bin/kasi probe t/probe/memory-remember.test
# In --ring sim (the merge gate) the agent block scripts the memory write; in
# --ring live the real agent runs and the assertion must hold for WHATEVER it writes.

send allow-sender    { address kasi@decode.ee }
send set-reply-from  { address kasi@decode.ee }

deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "remember my account"
    body    "Please remember this for future tasks: my Wise account ID is WX-40718 — use it for payments to me. Save it to your memory so you have it next time, then reply to confirm."
}

task 1 status is awaiting-agent

# Ring 1/2 script the turn; ring 3 runs the real agent, which must choose the memory
# gesture on its own from the worker prompt.
agent {
    out memory/wise-account.md "Wise account ID WX-40718 — use for payments to the owner."
    out reply.txt               "Saved your Wise account ID (WX-40718) to memory for next time."
}

task 1 status is awaiting-user

# The point of the probe: a real remember was recorded, so the collection is no
# longer empty. Naming-agnostic (the live agent picks its own file name), so this
# holds whether it saved one fact as `wise-account`, `wise-id`, or anything else.
memory count is 1

# The reply still sent (one mail, no memory attachment — a memory is a directive).
outbound count is 1
outbound last attachments is ""
